    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-04T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-04T07:00:00-05:00" n="1007"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1007">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.6354/137: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-04T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 4, 1939—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 4—8:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1424. Your 758, September 2, regarding tin; and your 774 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >772</hi>], September 3, 4 p.m., regarding rubber.<note n="84"
                        xml:id="d1007fn84">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_864">p. 864</ref>.</note> The
                    war has not only closed the Rubber and Tin Exchanges but has created great
                    dislocation in the Government departments concerned with these and other
                    matters. Officials are being transferred to newly created departments such as
                    the Ministry of Economic Warfare and Blockade; in many cases they are
                    unreachable and in any case they are snowed under by a host of problems they
                    have no time to deal with. Further dislocation will be caused when the air
                    bombardments begin. However, I have represented the importance to us of action
                    as regards both rubber and tin and as soon as the position clarifies itself a
                    little I shall do so again. In the meantime I should like to know whether we
                    will have sufficient shipping accommodation so that if necessary we can send our
                    own ships to Malaya to get supplies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
